        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Lee, that combination you're describing — disrupted sleep, lost appetite, dreading runs, and an elevated resting HR — that's your body sending a pretty clear signal, and I want to make sure we take it seriously together.\n\nHere's the thing: what you're experiencing isn't weakness or a bad patch. Those are recognized markers of accumulated fatigue, and they matter — not just for how you feel, but for whether your training is actually building fitness right now. When the body is in that state, hard sessions don't produce adaptation the way they normally would. You can put in the work and get very little return on it, or worse, dig the hole deeper.\n\nI also hear the urgency around the 10-week timeline. That's real, and I don't want to dismiss it. So let's think about this clearly: **10 weeks is actually enough time to recover, rebuild, and still arrive at the start line in the best shape of your life** — but only if we protect that window now. A week of reduced load isn't time lost. It's the investment that makes the next nine weeks productive.\n\nBefore I suggest anything specific — what's your sense of what's been driving the poor sleep? Is this training-related fatigue, or is there something else going on in life right now that's adding to the load?\n\nAnd one more thing I want to ask directly: how are you doing beyond the running? Sometimes when everything feels heavy and dread creeps in, it's worth checking in on the whole picture, not just the training log."
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_01KWt7LRmxidpSGp4BYpTGzH"
